# DevSecOps Pipeline: Execution Guide

This guide explains how to set up your repository for the JMeter and AI Dashboard integration and how to run components manually.

## 1. Repository Setup

For the Jenkins pipeline to work, ensure the following files are in the **root directory** of your repository:

- `Jenkinsfile`
- `jmeter-test.jmx`
- `ai-dashboard.py`

When Jenkins clones the repository, it will find these files automatically.

## 2. Using the AI Security Dashboard in Jenkins

Once the pipeline finishes:
1. Go to your Jenkins Job page.
2. Look for the **🛡️ AI Security Dashboard** link in the left sidebar.
3. Click it to see the unified security and performance report.

> [!NOTE]
> If the link doesn't show properly, ensure the **HTML Publisher Plugin** is installed in Jenkins.

## 3. Manual Execution (For Testing)

If you want to generate the dashboard manually on your EC2 instance:

### Run the AI Dashboard Script
```bash
# Ensure you have some reports in a 'reports' directory
python3 ai-dashboard.py
```
This will generate `reports/dashboard.html`.

### Run JMeter Manually
```bash
jmeter -n -t jmeter-test.jmx -l reports/manual-results.jtl -e -o reports/manual-html
```

## 4. SonarQube & App Access

- **SonarQube**: `http://<your-ec2-ip>:9000` (admin/admin)
- **Juice Shop App**: `http://<your-ec2-ip>:3000`

> [!TIP]
> If you cannot access these ports, check your **AWS EC2 Security Group** and ensure ports 8080 (Jenkins), 9000 (SonarQube), and 3000 (App) are open for your IP.
